"{\"uid\": \"salon.com-2024-08-13-breaking-olympics-raygun\", \"text\": \"Eddie the Eagle. The Jamaican bobsledding team. Great underdog stories are part of the Olympics\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 fabric, giving TV audiences supplemental heroes to cheer on. The most famous of these contenders have the hearts of champions if not the skills \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 although some, like the 1980 U.S. men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s ice hockey team, which was mainly comprised of amateurs,make history by pulling off miracles.  Rachael Gunn\\u00c2\\u00a0was never going to do that. The 36-year-old college professor said as much after she was eliminated from the Paris Games\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 breaking competition that left viewers alternately befuddled, delighted and enraged due to its confident awkwardness.  Gunn, who represented Australia in the b-girls competition under the moniker Raygun, was knocked out in the round-robin competition without scoring a single point.Worse, she was totally fine with that.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was never going to beat these girls on what they do best, the dynamic and the power moves, so I wanted to move differently, be artistic and creative, because how many chances do you get in a lifetime to do that on an international stage?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Gunn told reporters after the fact.  Maybe not so many. Or perhaps a lot more.\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00c2  In her battles, Gunn busted moves like \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthe kangaroo\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009chappy doggo rolling on a lawn,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d carrying herself like a combination of Chris Lilley\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSummer Heights High\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d character Mr. G andSacha Baron Cohen\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099sAli G.  While other competitors wore their favorite streetwear, Gunn wore her country\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s official tracksuit, which made her look like she was ready to either a) sell you some John Deere mowers; or b) assemble a Subway footlong to your specifications.  Raygun competes during the Breaking B-Girls Round Robin Group B battle between Logistx and Raygun on Day 14 of the Olympic Games Paris 2024 at La Concorde on August 9, 2024 in Paris, France. (Harry Langer/DeFodi Images via Getty Images)Days later her value as Internet gold is holding strong, as people try to make sense of what she was thinking, how she made it into a global competition purported to feature the best of the best athletes, and what on Earth she was doing. Was it uniqueness? A heroic expression of dancing like nobody\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s watching? A jaw-dropping example of cultural appropriation?  Yes. To all of it.  Related  Gunn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s presence in the Olympics' first and possibly only breaking competition didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t set off any alerts leading up to its debut, scheduled near the end of the 2024 Summer Games to maximize hype.  Most viewers know breaking as \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cbreakdancing,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d although calling it that will, at the very least, date you. \\u00c2\\u00a0Since the \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009890s b-boys and b-girls have competed in an assortment of international competitions, the most publicly promoted being the Red Bull BC One. \\u00c2  Bringing it to the Olympics was a play to attract younger viewers to the games, inspired by its popularity during the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics in Buenos Aires. Its combination of wide familiarity and relative novelty generated excitement among what the NBC commentators gamely called a \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cmore seasoned\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d viewership as well.  But there were always some doubts as to whether breaking belonged on the Olympics stage although it qualifies as a dance sport.  Gunn carried herself like a blend of Chris Lilley\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSummer Heights High\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d character Mr. G and Sacha Baron Cohen\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Ali G.  Breaking is also part of a subculture defined by authenticity although, as the multicultural vibrancy of the competitors showed, that term is a moving target.  Enter Gunn, who has a PhD in Cultural Studies and lectures at Macquarie University in Sydney. Gunn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doctoral thesis, titled \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDeterritorializing Gender in Sydney\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Breakdancing Scene: a B-girl\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Experience of B-boying,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d examines breaking from the lens of gender dynamics. At 355 pages long, one cannot accuse her of failing to think about her subject.  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the doing part that has made her either an object of mockery or a hero to the movement challenged. Or, as Dr. Stacey Patton sums up Gunn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s performance in a scathing NewsOne column, aparty to \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cmodern-day minstrelsy.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  A potential to generate anger was always lurking in the background of the International Olympic Committee\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s decision to add breaking to its program. Some are irked by the standardization of competitive breaking: Dancers strive to defy gravity and capture the music\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s spirit in spur-of-the-moment sculptures carved from their muscles, bones and imagination.  Olympics judges, however, were asked to score competitors on creativity, personality, technique, diversity, musicality and vocabulary.  And in the view of the Olympics\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 chief breaking judge Martin Gilian, aka MGbility, Gunn represented Australia by \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cbringing something new to the table. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009c[S]he got inspired by her surroundings, which in this case, for example, was a kangaroo,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009dhe told reporters, going on to add, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe was trying to be original and bring something new to the table. From our perspective, that was nothing really shocking.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  We need your help to stay independent  Except, maybe, to people who haven\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t followed breaking for years and were shocked at seeing Lithuania\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Dominika \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cNicka\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Banevic, a small, skinny white girl,bound out wearing a duraglike Tupac or LL Cool J.  Stylistic appropriation fades into a lesser sin if the person engaging in it shows reverence and understanding of the marginalized culture they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re drawing from. And Banevic, who won the silver medal, took time to acknowledge the original b-boys and b-girls after her win.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBig respect for the OGs and the pioneers that invented all those moves. Without them, it wouldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be possible,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009dshe said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWithout them, breaking wouldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be where it is today. So I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m grateful for them.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Gunn did not, and this separates her from those other underdogs mentioned above.  B-Girl Raygun of Team Australia and Logistx of Team United States react during the B-Girls Round Robin \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Group B on day fourteen of the Olympic Games Paris 2024 at Place de la Concorde on August 09, 2024 in Paris, France. (Elsa/Getty Images)Michael David Edwards, with his giant glasses, did not look like the typical champion ski jumper. Bobsledding is not big in Jamaica. While all share the commonality of being unconventional competitors in a space where they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re considered to be a rarity, bobsledding and ski jumping originated as European sports.  Breaking is different. \\u00c2\\u00a0Like the music and the rest of the culture, hip-hop\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s original movement form was born in New York and created in the late \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009870s by poor Black and brown kids living in the Bronx, who established its main cultural currency to be skillfulness and respect.  Pop culture\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s industries swiped music and fashion and left the dance form to Madison Avenue. Self-appointed mainstream ambassadors like Dena Rizzo,who was lampooned in a \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBob\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Burgers\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d episode, killed its mainstream popularity for good.  Breaking proliferated nevertheless, with crews popping up in countries around the world, including Australia. Like hip-hop, breaking is represented by a prismatic range of cultures, each of which has evolved the form and lends its own flavors.  Want a daily wrap-up of all the news and commentary Salon has to offer?Subscribe to our morning newsletter, Crash Course.  However, in a sport that began as physicalized rebelliousness by poor Black and Puerto Rican boys and girls in reaction to a government that had economically abandoned them, a white Australian woman proudly and mediocrely moving to her own beat was destined to get cooked on the searing barbie that is Black Twitter. \\u00c2  If we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re being honest, some of that smoke could be a matter of coming to terms with knowing the Americans weren\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t favored to medal in a dance sport created in the U.S.A. (Team USA did eke out a bronze, thanks to b-boy Victor Montalvo.)  Among the b-girls, the gold went to Japan\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Ami Yuasa, with China\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Liu Qingyi\\u00c2\\u00a0earning the bronze.  Gold medalist B-Girl Ami of Team Japan competes in her victory over B-Girl Nicka of Team Lithuania in the Breaking B-Girls Gold medal battle on day fourteen of the Olympic Games Paris 2024 at Place de la Concorde on August 09, 2024 in Paris, France. (Elsa/Getty Images)  It is also telling that many more people are talking about Gunn than 21-year-old Manizha Talash, an Afghan refugee who stepped into a battle wearing a cape that read \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cFree Afghan Women,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d knowing that would get her disqualified. (IOC forbids athletes from making political statements during competition.)  But that may have been Talash\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s biggest moment to use an international platform to send a message to the world. Before the Paris Olympics opened, it was already determined that breaking would not return in Los Angeles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 2028 summer games. It may not come back after that one, either. That makes every Paris b-boy and b-girl battle in this Olympics historic including, for better or worse, Gunn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s overnight notoriety.  With the games headed to Hollywood, it wouldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be surprising to see this discourse return as a movie, a la \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cCool Runnings\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEddie the Eagle.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Less clear is who would want to see this dark comedy repeated. But like Gunn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s moment at the heart of that Place de la Concorde arena, that might surprise us.  Read more  about this topic  Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026 Salon.com, LLC. Reproduction of material from any Salon pages without written permission is strictly prohibited. SALON \\u00c2\\u00ae is registered in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office as a trademark of Salon.com, LLC. Associated Press articles: Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2016 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.  DMCA Policy  By subscribing, you agree that Salon will automatically charge you at the then-current rate (currently $9.95/month or $95/year) each month/year until you cancel. Log in to your account anytime to cancel prior to renewal date and avoid future charges.  Your current signup type is\"}"